<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910313-0041</DOCNO><DOCID>910313-0041.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Travelers Corp.:   Executives' Compensation   Cut as Much as 26% in '90</HL><DATE>03/13/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><CO>   TIC</CO><IN>FULL LINE INSURANCE (INF)INSURANCE (INS)</IN><LP>   Travelers Corp.'s top executives took compensation cuts ofas much as 26% last year when the insurer posted a loss of$178.4 million.   According to Travelers' proxy statement for the scheduledApril 9 annual meeting, Edward H. Budd, chairman and chiefexecutive officer, earned $700,000 last year, down 26% fromhis 1989 compensation, which includes salary, bonuses anddirector's fees.</LP><TEXT>   Richard J. Shima, vice chairman and chief investmentofficer, took a 25% cut to $500,000. Thomas O. Thorsen, vicechairman and chief financial officer, earned $600,000, down9.7%.   Rounding out the Hartford, Conn., company's five mosthighly compensated executives for 1990 were Richard H. Booth,president and chief operating officer, who earned $488,458,and George A. McKeon, general counsel, whose compensationtotaled $479,231. No 1989 comparison figures were availablebecause Messrs. Booth and McKeon weren't in the top five lastyear. Securities and Exchange Commission rules requirecompensation disclosure of only the top five executives of acompany.</TEXT></DOC>